    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Is Youth the Answer?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Thomas E Curtin letter about April 15 article on New York Philharmonic says large-scale programming of modern works runs risk of alienating subscribers (M)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Passing the Baton: Be Bold New York'' [April 15]:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Passing the Baton: Be Bold New York'' [April 15]:</p>
        <p>In his discussion of the (perceived) needs for youth and a champion of modernism in the New York Philharmonic's next music director, Anthony Tommasini makes some valid points: Don't alienate mainstream subscribers, and it's vital to attract younger audiences. Both are critical to long-term survival. Nevertheless large-scale programming of modern works runs the risk of alienating subscribers. I haven't seen any credible data showing a correlation between modernist programming and younger audiences. A hot-shot music director may or may not be the answer.</p>
        <p>Thomas E. Curtin  Manhattan</p>
        <p>PHILHARMONIC LEADER</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
